# Solution

The apk file can be opened using an Android decompiler such as JADX-GUI or ByteCodeViewer.

The most interesting code is inside MainActivity:

We can see the following things:

* The application loads a native file ("theultimatequestion.so")
* When the application is launched, it calls getvault() which returns a base64 object. This object is decoded and loaded into memory through InMemoryDexClassLoader. 
* There is a getResourceString method that takes an identifier and returns a resource from a large array list

If you go into the resources and find R.array.parts, you will see that it contains a bunch of base64 encoded strings:

The code loops from 2 until 0x8b and calls getResourceString with the current counter value. It then appends all those different strings in one single buffer and returns the buffer.

We can write some python to replicate this behavior, or we can use Frida to dump the return value to a file:

ultimatequestion.js:
```javascript
function getVault(){

    let MainActivity = Java.use("be.dauntless.theultimatequestion.MainActivity");
    MainActivity.getVault.implementation = function(){
        console.log('getVault is called');
        let ret = this.getVault();
        console.log('getVault ret value is ' + ret);
        return ret;
    };
}
Java.perform(getVault)
```

Convert the base64 into a file. Either via terminal or via [Cyberchef](https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/#recipe=From_Base64('A-Za-z0-9%2B/%3D',true)&)

Open the file in a decompiler again. There's a bit of code to compare the password, followed by a lot of initialization functions:

```

    byte[] vault = new byte[71];

        ....

We can use Frida again to get the password, though it's not straightforward since the dex file is loaded dynamically. A much easier approach is to copy the Java code to a new Java project and run it:

```
public class MyClass {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
      Vault v = new Vault();
      System.out.println("Password: " + new String(v.sol));
      System.out.println("Flag: " + new String(v.vault));
    }
}
